TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Normative Model for Negotiations
AU  - Rao, Ambar G.
AU  - Shakun, Melvin F.
Y1  - 1974/06/01
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.20.10.1364
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.20.10.1364
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1364
EP  - 1375
VL  - 20
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Negotiations between a multinational corporation and a host government are considered for an international joint venture. Various negotiating behavior concepts that the two parties may use are discussed. The process of concession-making is formulated as a sequential decision problem, where each party has an opportunity for concession-making in alternating negotiation sessions, the magnitude of the concession depending on the current state of negotiations and the behavior concept being employed. A dynamic programming model is developed to yield normative recommendations as to concession-making. Numerical examples illustrating the model are presented.
AB  - Negotiations between a multinational corporation and a host government are considered for an international joint venture. Various negotiating behavior concepts that the two parties may use are discussed. The process of concession-making is formulated as a sequential decision problem, where each party has an opportunity for concession-making in alternating negotiation sessions, the magnitude of the concession depending on the current state of negotiations and the behavior concept being employed. A dynamic programming model is developed to yield normative recommendations as to concession-making. Numerical examples illustrating the model are presented.
